## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws.** The entire cooperative-abort model is gone.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be raised** — that `catch` block is dead code.

The .NET 8 pattern uses `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for graceful shutdown with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)))
        {
            // Task didn't finish in time — it's hung. Log a warning.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not exit within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a `Monitor.Wait` or unmanaged call, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` into blocking APIs (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take(token)`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync(token)`). |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | `Thread.Abort()` had no safe replacement. If your code can hang indefinitely, you need redesign — not a workaround. |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | A `volatile` flag can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` integrates with `WaitHandle`, so blocked waits get interrupted. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | The old `Stop()` used `Thread.Sleep(2000)` synchronously. Use `await Task.Delay()` or `Task.WhenAny` with a timeout instead. |
| **`Task.Run` vs `Thread`** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool (good). If your work is truly long-running, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |

### If you hosted this in ASP.NET, use `BackgroundService`:

```csharp
public class ItemProcessorService : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration in Program.cs:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<ItemProcessorService>();
```

This gives you lifetime management, graceful shutdown, and DI integration for free.
